This lovely patient, @elise_shahaesthetics, had her nose done by an outside surgeon elsewhere before she started working with me. Her nose suffered from some of the issues of using dated techniques, including asymmetric nasal bones , over projected tip, persistent deviation of the septum ,hanging columella, and bulbous nasal tip.

While creating a perfect rhinoplasty result is impossible, avoiding the obvious stigmata of a rhinoplasty is something I actively try to avoid. In her case, I used more updated techniques, including:

🚀Ultrasonic Rhinoplasty used to see entire bony platform 
👁My Complete Visualization Approach to seeing the entire anatomy of nose
➡️Total and True septoplasty to straighten entire septum 
5️⃣👃5D Rhinoplasty Tip Techniques to deproject and create nasal symmetry and shape

Her case was extremely difficult and extremely technical due to the fact that she had thicker skin and her previous rhinoplasty.  Her volumetric change was 8.0 cc which is a massive amount of change.  The stakes are always high for all of my patients, but Elise works in my office as a patient coordinator, so her nose is on full display for all of my patients.

“If your staff doesn’t TRUST you… Why should anyone else?”

TRUST is one of the hardest things to get from a patient. They have to believe in your surgical skills, your technique and you as a person. I do see a lot of staff from other offices who want to have surgery with rather than their own.

My staff gets to see many surgeries up close and personal so they know EVERYTHING about surgery and my techniques. While in theory she could have seen anyone else, Laura chose me because she trusted in me.

Stay tuned for more updates from Laura.

There is this old expression: “𝓑𝓮𝓪𝓾𝓽𝔂 𝓲𝓼 𝓟𝓪𝓲𝓷”
However what if we can improve this old expression with “𝓑𝓮𝓪𝓾𝓽𝔂 𝓦𝓲𝓽𝓱𝓸𝓾𝓽 𝓟𝓪𝓲𝓷”?

That’s the idea behind the Nerve Block technique that I adopt for Rhinoplasties.
This Nerve Block allowed patients to be numb for up to 3 days after the procedure and the beauty in this is:
⭐️ most of our patients don’t take any narcotic medication
⭐️ limited to no pain
⭐️ able to work or study from home the next day for many

Making beauty without pain should be the mantra to strike for!

I talk about this method which was published in Facial Plastic Surgery, a scientific journal, which I hope can be embraced by other surgeons as well.

Other surgeons Feel free to DM me to now more in details what and where  I exactly inject.

Honored to be presenting my approach to rhinoplasty at the Advances in Rhinoplasty and Facial Rejuvenation (@aafprs) meeting in San Diego. I always take a different approach to both my techniques and results. I’m using data that has not been reported before. I’m correlating this to create how I conceptualize some of my approaches.

Some things I’m talking about that I’ve never talked before:
1️⃣ How to raising mucosal flap consistently without tearing it.
2️⃣ How to consistently straighten the septum.
3️⃣ How to open up an airway, how to objectively measure airway volume, how to modify it, and why all of my talks have data supporting it.

I hope that this data I will be presenting will help improve the world of rhinoplasty and septoplasty.

It’s one of our favorite treatments for acne because you avoid antibiotics creams and your treatment will be aesthetic light.  This treatment is found to be more powerful than Accutane and antibiotics.

AviClear is Accutane-free, steroid free, and perfect for all skin types.

On her after, her nose is now significantly smaller and has true deprojection. Her nose now is in better balance with the rest of her face. She is only two months out and will continue to look better with time.

It seems so simple making a nose straight. However, it’s one of the most difficult things to do in rhinoplasty.

In this patient’s case, the bones were directly visualized and straightened using ultrasonic technology, straightened the septum by completely repositioning the septum, and then equalized the asymmetric anatomy to make the nose balanced.

Straightening the nose is one of the most difficult challenges in rhinoplasty. However, the rewards are sweet. It can lead to improved aesthetics and improve breathing and function.

This patient is 1 month out and not only is she happy with her aesthetics, she can breathe for the first time.

“𝐈𝐭’𝐬 𝐀𝐥𝐥 𝐀𝐛𝐨𝐮𝐭 𝐁𝐚𝐥𝐚𝐧𝐜𝐞.”

Bleph and brows. Why do I like doing them together? A lot of us have slight asymmetries in our face, including our brow and eye shapes. Balancing these out together can create a natural, more symmetrical balanced view. Here, our lovely patient can be seen the day of surgery as well as one month after.

With this approach, the patients can sometimes expect minimal bruising and swelling and look reasonably good soon after. This patient did this procedure under local anesthesia with nitrous in the office and was super comfortable throughout.

She had tried Botox and was unable to create the result and look she wanted. Now, she’ll have a permanent result that she was happy with on day one.

“𝚆𝚑𝚊𝚝 𝙼𝚊𝚔𝚎𝚜 𝙿𝚕𝚊𝚜𝚝𝚒𝚌 𝚂𝚞𝚛𝚐𝚎𝚛𝚢 𝚂𝚘 𝙷𝚊𝚛𝚍?”

Some really hard things to do in plastic surgery: Straighten the nose, revise the nose, deproject nose, lift the hyoid bone and create a neck when the deep contents of the neck aren’t there.

This patient traveled from afar to have all these things done and is 8 months out.

With specialized techniques that have taken years to fine tune, this patient was able to have her nose revised and deprojected. Also, had her hyoid  lifted up  so that she can have the neck contour and profile that she has always wanted.

Not only that, she has a better functional overall result. By straightening her nose, she’s able to breathe better, and by lifting her hyaloid, the patient’s snoring is improved as well. Some patients will have some functional improvement in their sleep.

These techniques are not easy to perform and represent the cutting edge of plastic surgery, and I’m super excited for this patient and her result.
